<A NAME = "23"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

ORIENTAL

Oriental Insurance Co Ltd (OIC), New Delhi, closed the year 1994-95
with an overall profit of Rs437.1m (US$12.3m).  Motor claims cost it
Rs1,950m.  Chairman KC Mittal said that although there was an
underwriting loss of Rs1,307.9m for the year after a profit of Rs118.5m
in 1993-4, this was essentially due to provisions for motor TPL claims
of Rs5,040m on 21 March 1995, compared with Rs2,730m int he previous
year, and resulting from changes to the Motor Vehicles Act and a trend
towards higher awards by claims tribunals.  He described MTPL claims as
"a bleeding wound" for the company and said there was a dire need for
increasing the third party insurance premium for buses and trucks.

Gross domestic premium income was about Rs11bn, up from Rs10.06bn.
Results in both fire and marine had substantially improved.  Foreign
operations in Nepal, Kuwait and Dubai yielded a revenue surplus of
Rs14.2m against a deficit of Rs40.8m.  Total investment earnings
increased by 20.9% to Rs1,785.1m.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "24"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

PROVINZIAL

German insurance agents are becoming increasingly worried about the
trend for established agency distribution insurers to set up direct
sales operations.  The agents' association Bundesverband Deutscher
Versicherungskaufleute said that more and more companies were becoming
"unfaithful".  The latest example was the plan of the Rhineland savings
banks, represented by Rheinischer Sparkassen- und Giroverband, together
with Provinzial Feuerversicherungsanstalt der Rheinprovinz, Dusseldorf,
to set up "S Direkt" in Spring this year to offer cheap motor cover.
According to a marketing analysis undertaken by the initiators, 14% of
potential customers were prepared to sign up with a direct sale
insurer.  The idea is also to increase penetration: while the 52
savings banks have a market share of close to 50% of households,
Provinzial has only 9%.  The savings banks will in future be major
shareholders of Provinzial.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "25"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

SAMPO

The Vantaa public prosecutor is suing three directors of Sampo Group,
Helsinki, Yritys-Sampo managing director Juhani Vesterinen, district
director Seppo Raty, and customer finance director Kari Vihurila, for
bribery for allegedly trying to influence the outcome of the bids for
covering the insurance risks of the City of Vantaa in 1994.  They are
alleged to have granted a loan to a company indirectly owned by Raimo
Salmivuo, who was chairman of the city council at the time.  The
accused deny the charges, and say that Yritys-Sampo bid for the
business was the best according to objective criteria and that any
loans made to Mr Salmivuo were on normal market conditions.  A hearing
in the Vantaa county court is due this month.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
