<A NAME = "26"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

SKANDIA

Forsakrings AB Skandia, Stockholm, offshoot Skandia Assurance &
Financial Services (AFS), which runs around 400 unit-liked insurance
funds, has set up a service company on the offshore tax haven of
Labuan, as well as in Borneo, which is currently home to 560 offshore
companies and 46 banks.  Skandia AFS South East Asia will be the
company's largest sales office in SE Asia, targetting Indonesia, the
Philippines, Brunei, Singapore, Thailand, Vietnam, China, Taiwan, and
Korea.

Elsewhere in Asia, the group has Royal Skandia in Hong Kong, which
sells unit-linked policies to expatriates working in the colony.
Skandia Asia chairman Bjorn Hall has forecast that pension monies would
grow by between 4% and 5% in real terms in the markets of Hong Kong,
China, Indonesia, Japan, Singapore, Malaysia Thailand, Korea, the
Philippines, and Australia in the coming years, and described India,
Burma, Sri Lanka and Cambodia as other up and coming markets.

Closer to home, Skandia's board has decided to take a more active role
as shareholder.  It will press for the establishment of nominating
committees, which propose candidates to boards, advise on their
remuneration, and propose auditors, in all joint stock companies.
Skandia will also encourage companies to give shareholders more
opportunity to prepare themselves for their AGMs by announcing them a
month in advance and publishing an agenda.  With over 30% of the
Stockholm stock exchange value in foreign hands, this should include an
English translation.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "27"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

TRYGG-HANSA

Trygg-Hansa AB, Stockholm, is aiming to double its premium income over
the next four years.  Ceo Lars Thunell believes that Swedish insurers
face tough competition from niche and foreign companies, and to survive
must halve their costs.  His method will be to double income while
holding expenses unchanged.  To achieve this, Mr Thunell plans new
distribution channels, simplifying products, improving services to
larger customers, as well as international expansion.  For the non-life
market the watchwords will be simplification and standardised products.
 Mr Thunell was resigned to slow progress at home, "nibbling half a
percent a year" in Sweden.  In addition, non-life products would
increasingly be sold by telephone and over the Internet, which should
allow penetration into Finland and Norway.  Slightly further afield, Mr
Thunell believed that the future markets were in the Baltic area.

Many of the lucrative opportunities were in the life market, he said,
as cutbacks in Sweden's social security and pension system opened the
way for new products combining savings and insurance.  This was a
further reason for the joint stock company (Trygg-Hansa AB)
strengthening its grip on Trygg-Hansa Liv (WICR177/18, 178/23, 183/22).
 A major step towards this consolidation was taken when the shareholder
agreement between SPP and Trygg-Hansa Liv was dissolved in late
December (WICR183/22).  This agreement involved Trygg-Hansa Liv and SPP
undertaking not to sell shares to third parties before the year 2000,
and thereafter offering first refusal to the other until 2010.

This paved the way for Trygg-Hansa Liv to pay SK626.5m (US$94.7m) to
buy 632,000 A shares and 5m B shares of Trygg Hansa AB from SPP.
Together with its existing holding of 19.4% of capital and 28.1% of
votes, this will give Trygg-Hansa Liv all of the 2m A shares in Trygg-
Hansa AB, and leave it with 26.2% of the capital in the company and
39.2% of the votes.  Trygg-Hansa Liv's chairman Gosta Wiking indicated
that the life company did not intend to take up any more Trygg-Hansa AB
shares, so that the outstanding packets were large enough to be
attractive to other institutional investors.

SPP still holds 16,447,512 B shares in Trygg Hansa AB, which have a
market value of around SK1.8bn at a market price of around SK110 a
share.  SPP has already adjusted these to SK98 per share on its balance
sheet (from SK 80), and a substantial proportion is likely to be sold.
The 16.44m shares represent 19.9% of Trygg-Hansa AB's capital and 16.3%
of the votes.  SPP spokesman Klas Rasater indicated that SPP was
unlikely to want to retain more than 5% in the long term.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
