<A NAME = "29"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

UAP

Cie UAP SA, Paris, and Interamerican Holding have announced that they
are to reorganise their current shareholding relationship within a
general co-operation agreement.  UAP will sell its 40% stake in
Interamerican Holding, which controls the interests of Interamerican
Property & Casualty Insurance Co, Athens, to Europolitan, Luxembourg.
Simultaneously, UAP's subsidiary Banque Worms, already a majority
shareholder in Interamerican Group member Interbank with 60%, will
become the sole shareholder.  The agreement will enable the
Interamerican Group and Interbank to enhance their joint capacity for
selling insurance products and banking services.  The Interamerican
Group will remain the representative of UAP in Greece.

UAP is proceeding with the restructuring of some of its main businesses
into two holding companies as announced at the end of last year
(WICR183/22).  UAP France became effective on 28 December 1995, and its
board met for the time on 3 January.

The minister of economy and finance (MoF) has also agreed to the
formation of UAP Collectives, which will be responsible for group life
within UAP France.  The MoF also authorised the transfer to it of the
portfolios of group assurance policies from UAP-Vie and UAP Incendie-
Accidents as of 1 January.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "30"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

VIETNAM INTERNATIONAL ASSURANCE

Commercial Union Assurance Co plc (CU), London, has received approval
from the Vietnamese ministry of finance to create the country's first
insurance joint venture involving overseas investment.  Vietnam
International Assurance Co, Ho Chi Minh City, has been formed in
conjunction with Ton Cong Ty Bao Hiem Viet Nam (Vietnam Insurance Co,
Baoviet), Hanoi, and Tokio Marine & Fire Insurance Co Ltd, Tokyo, and
is expected to commence writing non-life business in April once all the
appropriate licences have been approved.  The venture will have a paid-
up share capital of US$6m, Bao Viet controlling 51% and CU and Tokio
Marine taking an equal stake in the remaining 49%.  Vietnam
International is set to target industrial and commercial risks rather
than personal lines and aims to write about US$10m in premium income
within three years in order to for its operations to be viable.



