<A NAME = "33"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

WEST OF ENGLAND

The West of England Ship Owners Mutual Insurance Association
(Luxembourg) has warned that an "even greater level of self-insurance
is the only option" for members of the International Group if
uncertainty surrounding the future of the Lloyd's market continues and
no viable alternative is found.  In its annual review for 1995 the club
said that concerns remained about the International Group's heavy
dependence upon Lloyd's, which still writes up to 80% of the combined
layer of the International Group's reinsurance contract.  While there
had been "some optimism during recent months that Lloyd's would be
restructured", delays in Equitas meant that there was continuing
uncertainty over the future of the leading reinsurer for the club and
the Group and the prospect that "even greater levels of risk will have
to be retained within the industry", it said.

P&I providers could not expect to be immune from the type of litigation
that has "so bedevilled" the Lloyd's market over the past few years.
One way to prevent or defeat such litigation was for a club's
underwriters and committee to have a basic underwriting plan which
analysed potential exposure, laid down a policy to limit that exposure
acceptable to its members and then communicated that policy to them.
The club said that "unless and until the International Group introduces
a realistic limit on cover, a major overspill claim would inevitably
lead to litigation."  While the International Group had recognised the
need for limiting catastrophe liability calls to an "economically
collectable" level, its intention to have that level determined by an
independent expert after an event was troubling.  The club suggested
that a glance at the Lloyd's experience of trying to collect monies
owed from names would provide a "salutary lesson" to the International
Group about such a course.

Another challenge lay in the International Group's own Pooling
arrangements.  Since the individual club retention had increased
substantially in recent years from $1.2m per loss in 1989 to $5m in
1995, it was possible that the pattern of development of incurred pool
claims data will be different to that of the 1980s.  Whereas a claim
for $900,000 would have taken less time to appear in the pool, in 1995
a significant loss might take much longer to develop to the point where
it will concern the pool.  Claims information may therefore appear
unnecessarily optimistic.  The West of England concluded that "time
alone will tell", but urged club underwriters to take measures to
ensure that any negative impact may be minimalised.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "34"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

COLONIA LEBEN

Colonia Lebensversicherung AG (CL), Cologne, is set to turn its
Deutsche Crzte-Versicherung (DCV) branch operation into a company in
its own right.  According to its chairman, Carl Hermann Schleifer, CL
was currently discussing the legal and fiscal aspects of the
separation.  "By carrying out the spin-off, we break new ground," Dr
Schleifer said.  DCV will receive one-third of CL's existing portfolio,
which totalled DM62.5bn (US$43bn) at the end of 1995.  Dr Schleifer was
confident that a satisfactory solution would be found by this Spring,
and that DCV will then be turned into a separate joint stock company
retroactively from 1 January.  One major problem seems to be the offer
that has to be made to independent CL shareholders.

It is expected that DCV will eventually seek close co-operation with
Deutsche Apotheker-und Crztebank, Dusseldorf, the specialised bank for
the medical professions.  The small property and casualty unit Deutsche
Crzte-Versicherung Allgemeine AG, Cologne, which is already
independent, would not be affected by the separation.

Dr Schleifer, who also heads Nordstern Lebensversicherungs-AG and
private health insurer Colonia Krankenversicherung AG, also announced
another project of holding company CKAG Colonia Konzern AG,
establishment of a specialised consultancy and sales organisation to
concentrate on investments for customers over the age of 45.  A sales
force was currently being recruited in the banking sector who would not
only sell CKAG life insurance, but also funds, investment certificates
and other products.  Dr Schleifer said that former majority owner
Bankhaus Sal Oppenheim would certainly be a co-operation partner for
the new project, but that CKAG was also negotiating with other banks.
He added that the new organisation was one step in CKAG's strategy of
aiming at a new target group, the generation of the "young elderly".

Dr Schleifer displayed optimism regarding the prospects of life
business in Germany.  In his view life insurers would again benefit
from an improved economic environment and record growth in new business
in 1996.  He expects new business for both companies to rise by about
7% in 1996.  One major factor for the upturn would be the estimated
rise in the purchasing power of German consumers, which was expected to
be up by DM11bn (US$7.65bn) on 1995.  Germans were becoming
increasingly aware of the value of life policies as a provision for
their old age, Dr Schleifer said, adding that German life insurers had
not felt any effect from foreign competitors offering life policies in
the German market hitherto.  In his view, European Monetary Union would
bring no disadvantages for German insureds.

In 1995, Colonia Lebensversicherung AG (CL) suffered an 8.7% decline in
new business to DM7.5bn in sums insured.  "The market as a whole
anticipates a 13% fall in new business, so Colonia held firm and gained
market share," Dr Schleifer said.  He expected premium income for the
year to rise by 5.2% to DM1.9bn.  The cancellation ratio deteriorated
by 0.1 points to 4.7%, "but is still markedly below the market average
of above 6%", he said.  Sales by pyramid-sales company Proventus AG,
Bremen, accounted for less than 10% of newly sold business.  The
organisation did particularly well in selling private health cover in
eastern Germany.  "Overall, we are very satisfied with this sales
channel," Dr Schleifer said.

CL's cost ratio improved from 3.8% to 3.7%, mainly as a result of the
merger of the Colonia and Nordstern back-offices.  Dr Schleifer
expected a gross profit of DM593m for Colonia Life, up 4.4%.  Sister
company Nordstern Leben (NL) will outperform the rest of the market in
1995, the ceo said.  It maintained new business at the 1994 level, with
DM4.7bn in sums insured.  Premium income was expected to rise by 14% to
DM1.4bn, compared with an average growth of 7% in the German market,
although the cancellation ratio worsened from 3.7% to 4.3%.  NL's gross
profit will rise from DM276.7m in 1994 to an expected DM315m.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "35"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

ELAKE-SAMPO

The boards of Sampo Pension Insurance Co Ltd (Elake-Sampo), Helsinki,
and Pension-Varma Mutual Insurance Co (Elake-Varma), Helsinki, aborted
their planned transfer of insurance portfolios after failing to agree
on what form the reorganisation would take and methods of calculating
profits from the assets (WICR181/23).  The regulator, the ministry of
social affairs and health, had insisted on unanimity over the merger
arrangements as a precondition of its own approval.  A joint communique
stressed that auditors had found that there were no significant
differences in the financial situations of the companies, a move
designed to quash doubts over the soundness of the financial position
of Elake-Varma.

According to unofficial reports, one bone of contention was that Elake-
Varma wanted to assume a 10% future yield on shares, which others
considered unrealistic.  There were also differences over how to
estimate profits from hydro-electric power stations, which tend to be
heavily influenced by inflation expectations.  Elake-Varma owns several
such plants.  Consequently, there was some incredulity when the company
announced that the surplus of its insurance and investment activities
would increase from around FM40m (US$9.2m) for 1994 to nearly FM270m.

Elake-Varma managing director Paavo Pitkanen declined to speculate
whether another attempt to reorganise the two companies would be made,
while Elake-Sampo managing director Risto Kausto considered the matter
closed.

The other merger within the Sampo group, that of Kaleva Mutual
Insurance Co., Helsinki, and Nova Life Insurance Co Ltd, Helsinki, is
to proceed.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "36"></A>Copyright
WORLD CORPORATE INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

R+V

Germany's highest administrative court Bundesverwaltungsgericht in
Berlin, has issued an important ruling affecting demutualisation in the
country.  The court said that the German insurance supervision
Bundesaufsichtsamt fur das Versicherungswesen (BAV), Berlin, had acted
correctly when it allowed the 1989 transfer of the life portfolio from
the mutual R+V Lebensversicherungsverein aG to the joint stock company
R+V Lebensversicherung AG, Wiesbaden.

Several insureds of the old mutual had taken legal action against BAV,
complaining that the compensation paid to members was too low and did
not take the hidden reserves of the mutual adequately into account.  At
that time, a total of DM218m (US$152m) was paid to members to
compensate for their loss of that status.  The plaintiffs argued that
the hidden reserves totalled "a multiple" of that sum.

The court said that the BAV had taken sufficient care of the interests
of policyholders.  The legal and effective material situation of the
plaintiffs had not been worsened to a noteworthy degree.  As far as
they had suffered losses at all, they had been compensated.  The
transfer of the portfolio was no reason to dissolve the hidden
reserves.  The BAV's agreement to the deal did not prevent members from
suing for higher compensation.

The judgement is of considerable importance because it eases the
transformation from mutuals to joint stock companies.  Many mutuals
suffer from inadequate equity, and must increase capital through
profits.  The EU directive on the solvency of insurance groups which is
in preparation would aggravate the problem for life mutuals, as
reserves for premium repayments to policyholders would no longer count
as equity.



