<A NAME = "15"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

AMENDED LAW IN FORCE

The Insurance Amendment Act came into effect on 31 December.  As well
as increased minimum capital requirements, and more stringent licensing
requirements, the amendments increase the freedom of insurers to invest
in reserves.  Compulsory reinsurance cessions to Kenya Reinsurance
Corp, Nairobi, are to be phased out between this year and 1999.
Speaking at a reception last month, deputy insurance commissioner Sammy
Makove said that in future, the commission would publish annual lists
of insurance industry participants with valid licences, East Africa
Standard reported.  The publication of such a list in September
appeared to de-register hundreds of insurers, brokers, assessors and
surveyors (WIR523/7).  Some brokers and assessors de-registered at that
time continued to operate with some insurers, Mr Makove said, adding
that the Insurance Commission would continue to enforce licence
requirements.  Insurers should refuse business from unlicensed agents,
he added.

Of the two insurers "de-listed" in September, Mr Makove said that Co-
operative Insurance Service Ltd (CIS), Nairobi, had now met all
necessary requirements.  An auditor's report on state-owned Kenya
National Assurance Co, Nairobi (WICR181/20), was expected to be
completed by mid-December.

Meanwhile, insurers and brokers are in conflict over payment of the
compulsory 0.35% levy on gross direct premiums introduced by the
government in 1994 to fund the College of Insurance.  Attempts by
insurers to pass the costs on to policyholders are being resisted by
brokers, who allege such a step is illegal and are threatening court
action.  Cynical insurers suggest the complaining brokers merely wish
to be paid for collecting the tax.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
