<A NAME = "16"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

NEW SUPERVISION COMMISSION

In December the Ugandan parliament passed legislation to establish an
independent Uganda Insurance Commission to oversee the industry,
responsible to the Finance Ministry.  Insurance was formerly supervised
by the Central Bank along with all other financial institutions.  The
Commission will issue regulations on the conduct of insurance and
reinsurance and intermediary activity, licence individuals involved in
insurance, and deal with complaints by policyholders.

Minister of State for Finance Matthew Rukikaire told parliament that
existing insurance legislation was "grossly inadequate".  Minimum
capital for a locally-owned insurer will increase to USh200m
(US$198,400), an increase which it is hoped will be sufficient to
remove from the market so-called "briefcase" companies (also known
locally as "quark insurers", presumably because they vanish with the
speed of light).  Sebaana Kizito MP, head of Statewide Insurance Co
Ltd, Kampala, argued for an increase to USh500m, a measure he said was
supported by the Uganda Insurance Association and the Uganda Insurance
Institute.  Foreign-owned insurers will be required to have minimum
capital of USh1bn for life or non-life, USh2bn for composite companies
and USh2.5bn for reinsurance activity.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "17"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

MORE CATS, LOSSES LOWER

While indications have become stronger during 1995 that the gradually
changing world climate is having an effect on the occurrence of natural
catastrophes, especially floods and windstorms, insurers suffered fewer
losses from such events last year, Munchener Ruckversicherungs-Ges AG,
Munich, said in its annual report on catastrophes.  The year 1995 had
provided a "breathing space for the insurance industry, which has been
having to cope with particularly heavy claims burdens from natural
catastrophes for nearly ten years," it added.

The company also drew attention to an important and mainly positive,
factor: the long-lasting El Niuo effect, a natural cyclical warming of
the tropical Pacific, came to an end in 1995.  El Niuo had resulted in
extreme drought in Australia and heavy rainfall on the US Pacific
coast, but had also contributed to a reduction of hurricane activity in
the Caribbean.

According to Munich Re, the number of events it categorises as natural
catastrophes rose from 580 in 1994 to about 600 in 1995 which claimed a
total of 18,000 lives, up from 10,150.  In terms of economic losses,
1995 was a record year, the total of US$180bn dwarfing the $65bn of
1994, the previous worst year.  In 1995, however, insured losses
reached only $14bn, compared to $28bn in 1992 and $17bn in 1994.  This
resulted from the fact that insurance density in the regions most badly
affected in 1995 was comparatively low.

This applied in particular to what was, in economic terms, the most
expensive natural catastrophe to date, the Great Hanshin Earthquake
which struck Kobe on 17 January and caused overall losses of about
$100bn.  Although of only medium intensity, it reduced parts of the
industrial and port city to rubble and ashes.  More than 6,000 people
were killed and 300,000 left homeless.  Other notable events during
1995 were the January floodings of the rivers Rhine, Moselle and Maas,
only 13 months after similar occurrences, and tropical windstorms in
the Caribbean, the US and East Asia.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "18"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

DISASTERS BILL UNDER FIRE

At hearings before the US House Transportation & Infrastructure
Committee's Water Resources & Environment subcommittee at the beginning
of December, the proposed Natural Disaster Protection Partnership Act
came under severe criticism by Rep Mike Parker (R-MS) as "a public-
sector solution to a private-sector problem".

The legislation proposes the establishment of a private sector insurer
to provide homeowners' cover and reinsurance in areas at high risk from
natural disasters.  Mr Parker said that a clause which would permit the
entity to borrow from federal government should its reserves be
depleted by a major catastrophe would make the government liable for
the insurance industry's risks.

In his testimony to the Committee, Deputy Assistant Secretary of the
Treasury Mozelle Thompson recommended an approach combining state-
regulated mandatory disaster insurance with a federal reinsurance
programme rather than the federal corporation proposed in the Act.  Mr
Thompson feared that the proposed National Disaster Insurance Corp
could develop into a monopoly, placing policyholders at a disadvantage.
 He said the Clinton administration feared that the Act could expose
the government to unlimited liabilities, and had reservations about the
financial viability of the scheme.

He proposed instead development of "a required phased-in policy" for
dwellings for up to four families mortgaged with federally-related
lenders or secondary issuers, administered by states, together with a
federal excess of loss programme through the mechanism of an annual
auction of contracts covering a proportion of the loss from a single
natural disaster, triggered by industry-wide insured losses and with a
base price set in line with risk plus a cost of capital adjustment.
The programme would be designed to phase itself out between years 15
and 20 of operation.



