WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

STORM INSURANCE PREMIUMS TO RISE

In mid-November, the Florida Windstorm Underwriting Association filed a
request to the Insurance Department for an average rate increase of
67%, the first since 1981.  The annual premium for a house in Miami
Beach valued at US$113,000 and insured by the Association would rise
from $185 to $461, and in St. Petersburg Beach from $222 to $407, but
in St. Augustine Beach, the premium would fall from $222 to $205.  The
Association said that an independent actuarial assessment had
recommended an average increase of 124%, and that it had incurred a
loss in excess of $192m for claims in 1995.  Its rates are currently
significantly below those for other residual markets for homeowners in
Florida and in other states, as well as some rates in the private
sector, it said.  The Association insures 223,000 policyholders and has
total exposure of $35bn.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "21"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

TAX BREAK "CRITICAL" FOR EQ PLAN

A proposed new earthquake insurance programme in California, given
preliminary approval by the state legislature on the last day of its
session in October, will require confirmation of tax-exempt status from
the Internal Revenue Service to be viable, deputy insurance
commissioner Richard Wiebe said.  This would force the state to
consider other alternatives, such as an involuntary insurance pool, he
added.

The proposed California Earthquake Authority will have access to funds
of up to US$10.5bn.  The California Insurance Department proposes a
premium rate of $3.10 per $1,000 of insured house value.  An initial
$1bn in funding for the Authority would be provided by insurers,
together with a guarantee of $3bn in the event of claims.  $2bn in
reinsurance would be bought in excess of this figure.  Last month
Insurance Commissioner Charles Quackenbush toured Bermuda, London, New
York and Zurich in search of potential capacity, where reaction was
favourable, Mr Wiebe said.  Brokers for the reinsurance element will be
EW Blanch Holdings Inc.  Losses above $6bn will be covered by an issue
of state bonds for $1bn, and a further $1.5bn in bonds placed on the
New York stock market by Morgan Stanley as lead manager, co-managed by
Bear Stearns and Goldman Sachs.  A further $2bn would be paid by the
insurance industry on a contingency basis, bringing the Authority's
total capital to $10.5bn.

The Insurance Department hopes to deliver an interim report on progress
of the plan in the near future, and secure final approval by the end of
March.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "22"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

"FAIR TORRENT" OF SNOW CLAIMS

While blizzard conditions brought a white Christmas to Scotland,
Northern Ireland, Wales and northern parts of England, the subsequent
New Year thaw has caused estimated damage of #350m (US$545m) according
to loss adjusters, The Balcome Group, London.  The group's initial
estimate of #500m in insured damage was refuted last week by the
Association of British Insurers (ABI), London.  Share analysts
variously predict the likely eventual cost to UK insurers at about
#400m, or #20m to #30m off the net profit of each of the UK composites.

UK insurers are receiving a "fair torrent" of claims after this "major
incident", an ABI spokesman told WIR, but insured damage was more
likely to total #100m to #200m rather than #300m to #500m.  It will be
several weeks before the official ABI estimate is known.  The majority
of claims are expected in Scotland, Northern Ireland and north east
England, primarily for household damage following burst pipes,
commercial water damage and business interruption.

Significant claims are also expected to arise from commercial users of
water following the failure of water supplies, he added, although some
businesses would be self-insured or lack appropriate cover and there
would be significant uninsured damage for householders in Scotland.

Increased weather damage claims recorded over the past week are still
within normal expectations and unlikely to lead to higher premiums,
according to UK insurers.  A spokesman for Royal Insurance plc, London,
told WIR that an increased number of claims were coming in, but it was
too early to estimate the total number.  Claims would be concentrated
in Scotland and north east of England, unlike in 1991 and the 1980s
when cold weather affected the whole country, he added.  Royal expects
the greatest number of claims from household damage, but commercial
claims to cost more.  Commercial Union plc, London, said it was too
early for definite numbers, but claims were likely to be "more than
usual".  As of 3 January, the company had received 1,500 claims.  Sun
Alliance Group plc, London, said the number of claims would be
significantly "up, not under".



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "23"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

BUILDING CODE PROPOSED

Insurers in the Caribbean region have been reminded by the Council of
Caribbean Engineering Organisations (CCEO) of the need to improve risk
management methods if they wish to achieve better rates from
international reinsurers.  One way, it suggested, is for insurers to
throw their weight behind the introduction of mandatory building codes
as a means of minimising damage from natural hazards.  Only three
Caribbean countries, two of them British colonies (the Bahamas,
Anguilla and Monserrat) have such codes.

The Barbados-based CCEO is in the final phase of drawing up a
comprehensive Caribbean Uniform Building Code (CUBIC), which it would
like adopted by all the other 12 members of CARICOM, the Caribbean free
trade area.  The code will outline the design and construction
parameters for all new buildings.  The organisation would like the
insurance industry to be more active in pressing governments to enforce
the Code, a spokesman said, and with the Caribbean just having
experienced its worst hurricane season for 62 years and insurers still
counting the costs, it feels the industry, with the prodding of
reinsurers, may now be ready to take notice.

Tony Gibbs, a senior Caribbean engineer who has been one of the most
active in promoting CUBIC, said Caribbean insurers would be doing
themselves a favour by supporting mandatory building standards, if only
because "it will remove an easy excuse for the high catastrophe
insurance premiums the region must bear at the present time".

One reason why most Caribbean governments have not moved to enforce the
Code is a desire to avoid raising building costs.  Mr Gibbs said that a
recent study showed that were CUBIC adopted, only between 0.24% and
2.2% would be added to total costs.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "24"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

1996 CAPACITY

Lloyd's underwriting capacity in 1996 will be #9.852m (US$15.3m), down
from #10.195m in 1995,  according to provisional figures.  Individual
names will contribute #6.841m (down from #7.835m), #2.586m through
bespoke underwriting and #4.255m through MAPAs, and corporate vehicles
#3.011m (up from #2.360m).  The number of individual names will fall
from 14,884 to 12,811 (only six new members joined for the year), and
the number of corporate names rise to 165 in 71 corporate member
groups.  25 new corporate names raised an additional #362m in capacity
for 1996, and existing corporate members increased allocated capacity
by #289m.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "25"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

IN THE COURTS

On 21 December, Mr Justice Gatehouse found "with considerable
hesitation" that no competent members' agent could have placed names on
Feltrim syndicate 540/2 in 1990 (although some categories of names
failed to demonstrate their case), and "with more confidence" that the
names case failed with regard to syndicate 847.

On the same day, the Court of Appeal upheld the "pay now, sue later"
ruling by Mr Justice Rix in Marchant & Eliot Ltd v Higgins (WIR524/9).
Lloyd's served approximately 300 writs on recalcitrant names the same
day.

On 6 December, Lloyd's was also successful in a High Court action, also
heard by Mr Justice Gatehouse, in which Diana Aldrich sought to prevent
drawdown on her Lloyd's deposit because she claimed to have been
fundamentally mistaken about the nature of Lloyd's when she became a
name.  The case was summarily dismissed.

On 3 January, the Colorado Court of Appeal partially reversed a Denver
District Court preventing drawdown on Colorado names' deposits in an
action initiated by the state securities commissioner.  Meanwhile, an
outline settlement with the 700-odd members of the American Names
Association has been agreed in principle by Lloyd's.

As a result of the decision of Mr Justice Cresswell in Henderson et al
v Merrett Syndicates Ltd et al (WIR524/1), E&O insurers served the
victorious Pulbrook 334 (1985) names with a notice of intention to
avoid payment (WIR506/1).  The names have begun liquidation proceedings
against Pulbrook U/W management Ltd, London.

The appeal by the Gooda Walker Action Group on the issue of the
taxation of awards will be heard by the House of Lords on 16 January.



