<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "29"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

VETO TO BE OVERTURNED?

President Bill Clinton decided in December to veto congressional
proposals to limit court awards for liability damages (WIR525/11).  The
House of Representatives voted to override the veto on its bill, which
as part of the so-called Contract with America would limit damages in
all cases, including medical malpractice.  The Senate appeared likely
to try to take similar action, a two-thirds majority being required to
overturn the veto.  The bill would be the first to be enacted after a
Clinton presidential veto.

A joint congressional committee had met briefly on 15 December to try
to reconcile the differences between the House bill and that in the
Senate, which is restricted to product liability.  No date was set for
a further meeting, the staff of committee members being requested to
reach agreement on as many issues as possible beforehand.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "30"></A>Copyright
WORLD INSURANCE REPORT via NewsNet
January 12, 1996

CALIFORNIA PROPOSES NO-FAULT

Three initiatives to be put before the California electorate in March
could have important implications for insurers.  Propositions 200 to
202, which are being presented as a package by proponents, would
introduce no fault motor insurance in the state (200), require in most
cases that the losing party in class and shareholder actions alleging
breach of securities legislation to pay the costs of the victor (201),
and limit contingency fees to 15% if defendants in tort cases offer
early settlement in response to a mandatory demand letter (202).

Meanwhile, California motor insurers are lobbying against new anti-
redlining measures announced by Insurance Commissioner Charles
Quackenbush, which will force insurers to apply greater weight to
driving records and less to where the vehicle is garaged.  Insurers
suggest that the cost of reconfiguring databases will be huge and
passed on to policyholders, and that premium increases of up to 175%
may result.



